    <bioghist encodinganalog="545">
      <p>The Arthur Ingraham Martindale collection contains the family records and papers of Edward Ingraham (1812-1881) and his wife Amelia (1822-1916). The Ingrahams were a prominent shipping and logging family who in Old Saybrook, Connecticut. Edward and Amelia were married on January 15, 1844 and had seven children between 1845 and 1865. Edward was a partner in H.D. Braddock &amp; Co. of Bay City, Michigan, a logging business begun in 1855 by a group of men who agreed to "associate themselves together in the business of purchasing timber lands, erecting mills, and manufacturing and selling lumber." However, the partnership was dissolved in 1863 when Edward bought out the rest of his partners.</p>
      <p>One of Edward and Amelia's sons, Arthur Hancock Ingraham (1852-1938), married Mary Ann Mercer in 1877. Edward Ingraham passed away in 1881, at which time Amelia, and eventually Arthur, took over management of the family business. Arthur and Mary Ann resided in Bay City, Michigan. Unfortunately, the Ingraham family estate in Old Saybrook burned down in a fire in 1915. Although the house was rebuilt, and many of the family and business records were destroyed.</p>
      <p>Arthur Ingraham Martindale, Arthur Hancock Ingraham's grandson, was born on February 10, 1910. This collection is named after him, given that he was the original collector of the materials. The collection was further expanded upon by Arthur's children, Marguerite Martindale Braden, Patricia Martindale Tripoli, Shirley Martindale Roberts, Helen Martindale Roberts, and Arthur Stephen Martindale, who donated the materials to the Bentley Historical Library in 2012- 2013.</p>
    </bioghist>
    <scopecontent encodinganalog="520">
      <p>This collection is comprised of family letters and business records from the Edward Ingraham family. The materials were first collected by Arthur Ingraham Martindale, and were further arranged by Arthur's children. Materials are divided into two series: the Marguerite M. Braden series and the Helen Martindale Roberts series.</p>
    </scopecontent>
